  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Kushchi Dairy and Hog Farm Improvement Project</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In the Georgian village of Kushchi, families struggle with poor nutrition and unemployment. This project will assist a total of 107 families. Forty-six families will receive either a local breed dairy heifer or a sow, an additional 46 families will receive an animal pass on, and 15 families will benefit from the passing on of knowledge from trainings.  In addition to livestock and fodder, all participating families will receive training in advanced farm and animal management, as well as technical assistance and veterinary medicine to establish and run their own small-scale dairy and hog farms. For this project, the project holder decided that all animals will be kept in a community barn where the different project participants will take turns caring for the animals. Project participants will grow fodder on the land adjacent to the barn.  Milk from the project cows will be made into cheese and distributed to the project participants according to a schedule. Over three years, with the assistance of Heifer Georgia, project participants will improve their community&#x2019;s food security, increase incomes and nutrition levels through milk and pork production and consumption, and create opportunities for women in the village to start livestock-based micro-enterprises.</narrative>
  </description>
